At [123], the Tribunal held that, whilst in the absence of the Domestic Fallback Rule the claim in respect of cross-border transactions would be complete, the claim in respect of domestic transactions could not be advanced in its absence. In the result, “[o]n the basis explained in [
		The Kriti Palm
	      ] this clearly gives rise to a distinct cause of action”. But, looking at the substance rather than the form of the pleading demonstrated that the claimants put forward “as a matter of substance these two distinct claims, by reference to the Decision”. The effect of the EEA MIF on the Domestic MIFs was not “merely a matter of causation resulting in further harm. It was not foreseeable that the setting of a MIF for cross-border transactions would in itself have an effect on domestic transactions”.
